But Hebrew still has hints of vowels in its consonantal alphabet, that helps readers with the pronunciation.  A vav can be a V sound, but with the right dot (as you said, not reproduced in point-free text), it can sound like long O or U.  A he at the end of a word generally signals an "ah" or "eh" ending.  A yod can be a consonantal Y at the beginning of a word, or an I elsewhere (as in the word that means "Israeli).  Alephs and ayins are supposedly "silent letters," but there's an unseen vowel below it if there are no printed points.

Still, reading Hebrew without the points is difficult for the casual learner, but still, the native speakers do it.

